Particular languages had their own images, masculine or feminine. For
example, the idea that the Germanic languages were especially manly was a
commonplace. In his essay-oration On the Excellency of the English Tongue,
the English scholar-poet Richard Carew described what he called ‘Dutch’
(probably German) as ‘manlike’. The Welsh writer James Howell described
both German and English as masculine languages. John Dryden noted
the ‘masculine vigour’ of English and contrasted it with French. The poet
Friedrich Gottlieb Klopstock described German as mannlich. Other lan¬
guages might also be described in this way on occasion: Montaigne, for
instance, called Gascon ‘un langage masle et militaire’, while the historian
