language is a rough indicator of the prestige of that language.
Translations into a particular language, on the other hand, may be read as
a sign that that culture was relatively open to foreign ideas. Italian imports
were relatively high, especially in the sixteenth century and from Spanish.
French imports were also high in the sixteenth century, with 1570—1600
as the peak period for translations from Italian (translations from Spanish
peaked a little later).80 England too had a high level of imports from Italian,
Spanish and French (about four hundred and fifty translations from Italian
were published between 1550 and 1660).81
In the case of Spain, on the other hand, imports seem to have been
