and Sami. In 1757, Romanian.
The publication of a grammar of a given vernacular does not of course
mean that even a minority of the speakers of that vernacular were actually
following the rules. All the same, the spread of the grammars is impressive
and, in the case of a few vernaculars, the rules appear to have been taken
seriously by elites.
It might be said that certain vernaculars won the battle with Latin by
ceasing to be vernaculars, by creating a sort of‘authorized version’ of lan¬
