However, the mixing of languages at global level began centuries ago. In
early modern times it was a consequence of the invasion of the rest of the
world by Europeans, otherwise known as ‘discovery’ or ‘empire-building’.
Portuguese was the first to expand its domain, followed by Spanish, French,
Dutch and English.5
Similar processes of hybridization had been taking place within Europe
for a long time. In medieval England, for example, English, French and
Latin were in constant interaction, and the borrowing of Scandinavian
words was so important that some linguists speak of ‘pidginization’ and
‘creolization’ in Middle English. However, this chapter will argue that bor¬
