by relatively few people, Maltese for example, reveals the mixing process
more clearly than a language spoken by millions. In the later fifteenth
century, Maltese was essentially a dialect of Arabic. By the late eighteenth
century, on the other hand, it bore many traces of Sicilian, Catalan, French
and north Italian.6
