## LANGUAGE LEARNING
A number of early modern rulers, ministers and diplomats are known to
have spoken several European languages. William the Silent, for instance,
who governed the Netherlands during the struggle for independence from
Spain, knew French, Dutch, German and Spanish. The emperor Leopold
knew Latin, Italian and Spanish as well as his native German. Erik xiv of
Sweden is said to have known five foreign languages - German, Italian,
Spanish, French and Finnish.10
Like their masters, ambassadors knew languages better than most. John
Hackett, Henry viii’s ambassador in the Low Countries, is said to have spo¬
ken six languages, English, Latin, French, Spanish, Flemish and Italian).11
