the century, the Calvinist humanist Theodore Beza would use the same
technique in his satire on the Church of Rome, the Passavant. Texts such
as these well illustrate the interanimation of three languages or varieties,
classical Latin, medieval Latin and the vernacular.103
In similar fashion, the mixing of different vernaculars, whether languages
or dialects, was deployed for comic effect by writers and especially by
playwrights.
Panurge, for example, when he first meets Pantagruel in chapter nine of
Rabelais’s romance, speaks to him in two invented languages and ten real
ones, German, Italian, English, Basque, Dutch, Spanish, Danish, Hebrew,
Greek and Latin. Rabelais was extremely interested in language and in the
linguistic debates of his day, as various chapters of Gargantua and Pantagruel
show quite clearly.104
