An even more remarkable example of language mixing, two hundred
years before Mozart, comes from the letters of the musician Roland de
Lassus, otherwise known as Orlando di Lasso. Lasso was a francophone
from Mons, who had lived in Italy before entering the service of Wilhelm
Duke of Bavaria. He wrote French chansons, Italian madrigals, German
Lieder and Latin hymns with apparently equal ease. He was on intimate
though deferential terms with his young patron (the duke was in his twenties
