However, the process of inter-animation did not come to an end in 1600.
When multilingual plays ceased to be popular, in the early seventeenth cen¬
tury, they were succeeded by comedies displaying the varieties of speaking
associated with different social groups, as in the case of Moliere or his
equivalents in eighteenth-century Venice and Scandinavia, Carlo Goldoni
