five languages spoken in the realm, which made the English as worthy as
the Germans to be classified as a nation.4
All the same, the association between a people and its language expressed
by the term lingua is a revealing one. In the later Middle Ages, as some
vernaculars entered the domains of literature and administration, language
was becoming a source of pride, identity and consequently of conflict. If a
people that had previously been independent became part of an empire, it
might be allowed to retain its official language. Hence, in 1527, Ferdinand
of Austria promised those Hungarians who lived in the Habsburg Empire -
the rest were now under the rule of the Turks - that he would preserve ‘your
