it seems that the link between language and national consciousness was
forged around the year 1770 in the course of a reaction against a regime in
which a German, Count Struensee, had exercised power. Before this time,
the coexistence of German and Danish appears to have been politically
## ‘unproblematic’.20
In the course of the French Revolution, the ‘politics of language’
came to the fore, especially in 1793, when fear of counter-revolution was
widespread.21 Bertrand Barere, a member of the Committee for Public
Safety, called for a revolution in language, in order to combat ‘federalism
