role of the school, the army, the media of communication and, not least,
the part played in the unification of the language by the new capital city,
Rome, and by its bureaucracy, recruited as it was from different parts of the
peninsula and thus unable to communicate in anything but the standard
language.28
As in the case of the so-called ‘rise of the vernaculars’, however, the
temptations of Whig or triumphalist history must be avoided. Once again,
an emphasis on competition is in order. The simple model of‘one nation,
one language’ did not fit many parts of Europe. What looked from the centre
like unification was viewed from the periphery as cultural invasion, an at¬
