Despite these attempts at homogenization, varieties of language proved
impossible to suppress. In Belgium, we need to speak of ‘triglossia’
rather than diglossia, a situation of competition and conflict not only
between French (the language of administration, the upper classes, and the
Walloons) and Flemish (the language of the majority of the population),
but also between Flemish and Dutch, a more standardized variety of the
same language.32
Norway offers another illustration of the competition between varieties
